{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506618"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2553"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2553"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.3,0.05,0.33,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78390"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2553"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63752"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"},{"type":"tags","id":"1862"},{"type":"tags","id":"1947"},{"type":"tags","id":"2806"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6219"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43187"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78390"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of worsening back pain. The pain started insidiously and is most severe in the mornings with stiffness lasting 60-90 minutes, gradually improving with activity throughout the day. She experiences episodes of aching pain in the sole of her right foot, most noticeable when walking. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reports an episode of conjunctivitis one month ago and a recent chest infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are fine crepitations at the right lung base. The remainder of the examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of axial spondyloarthritis is considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features would best support this diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No response to nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs","Recent conjunctivitis","Female sex","Plantar fasciitis","Bibasal fine crepitations"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of axial spondyloarthritis, including inflammatory back pain (morning stiffness improving with activity) in a young person. The diagnosis requires consideration of clinical features, imaging, and laboratory findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar fasciitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a recognised extra-articular manifestation of axial spondyloarthritis and would support the diagnosis. The patient\u0027s foot pain while walking is consistent with this finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo response to nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs\u003C/strong\u003E would actually argue against the diagnosis, as good response to NSAIDs is a characteristic feature of inflammatory back pain seen in axial spondyloarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecent conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with axial spondyloarthritis. However, anterior uveitis (which presents differently from conjunctivitis) is a classic extra-articular manifestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemale sex\u003C/strong\u003E does not support the diagnosis, as axial spondyloarthritis is more common in males. However, it can certainly occur in females and sex alone cannot rule out the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBibasal fine crepitations\u003C/strong\u003E are not characteristic of axial spondyloarthritis. While pulmonary involvement can occur, it typically presents as apical fibrosis rather than basal changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther extra-articular manifestations of axial spondyloarthritis include inflammatory bowel disease, psoriasis, and peripheral arthritis. The diagnosis is supported by HLA-B27 positivity and characteristic changes on imaging, particularly of the sacroiliac joints.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Axial spondyloarthritis typically presents in patients under 40 years with inflammatory back pain characterised by morning stiffness and improvement with activity.","Extra-articular manifestations supporting axial spondyloarthritis include anterior uveitis, plantar fasciitis, and apical (not basal) pulmonary fibrosis.","Response to NSAIDs is a characteristic feature of axial spondyloarthritis and helps distinguish it from mechanical back pain."],"references":["Chen HH, Chen TJ, Chen YM, Ying-Ming C, Chen DY. Gender differences in ankylosing spondylitis-associated cumulative healthcare utilization: a population-based cohort study [published correction appears in Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2012 Sep;67(9):1123]. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2011;66(2):251-254. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21484042/","Ankylosing Spondylitis. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63752"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2553"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63752"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T14:34:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T14:34:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2553"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78390"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitab